# SentinelOps Project Rules

## Project Identity
You are helping build SentinelOps — a self-healing ML inference platform on Kubernetes with Claude-based remediation.

## Stack
- Infra: Terraform, k3d (local), AWS EKS (Phase 2)
- ML: Kubeflow Pipelines (standalone), MLflow, LightGBM, DistilBERT
- Serving: KServe, Istio, FastAPI transformer
- Events: Redpanda (Kafka-compatible)
- Observability: Prometheus, Grafana, Loki
- Safety: OPA Rego policies
- AI: Claude API with tool-use for remediation agent
- GitOps: ArgoCD
- Chaos: Chaos Mesh

## Environment
- Windows host, WSL2 Ubuntu 24.04 LTS (all work happens in WSL2)
- Docker Desktop with WSL2 backend, 11GB RAM / 8 CPUs allocated
- Working dir: ~/sentinelops in WSL2 (never /mnt/c/)
- Python 3.11 for all services

## Coding Conventions
- Terraform: modules in infra/terraform/modules/, environments in infra/terraform/envs/
- Helm values: separate YAML files in infra/helm-values/, referenced from Terraform helm_release
- Python: type hints required, structlog for logging, pytest for tests, ruff for linting
- Dockerfiles: multi-stage builds, distroless/alpine base where possible
- Naming: kebab-case for K8s resources, snake_case for Python, PascalCase for classes
- Commit messages: conventional commits (feat:, fix:, chore:, docs:, refactor:)

## Critical Rules
- NEVER use /mnt/c/ paths in WSL2 — always use ~/ (Linux filesystem)
- NEVER commit secrets, .env files, AWS credentials, or model artifacts
- NEVER expose services without Istio in front (after Day 6)
- ALWAYS wrap kubectl/kustomize commands in Terraform null_resource for IaC
- ALWAYS test commands with --dry-run or terraform plan before apply
- ALWAYS check pod status with `kubectl wait` after deploys, never assume readiness

## Day-by-Day Discipline
- Every day ends with a commit + push + daily-log entry in docs/daily-log.md
- Phase 2 (AWS days): MANDATORY `terraform destroy` at end of every session
- Resource budget: project must stay under $100 AWS spend total

## MLflow Sourcing (added Day 3)
- DO NOT use community-charts/mlflow Helm chart for MLflow 3.7+ — it has
  unresolved compatibility issues (chart hasn't caught up to MLflow 3.7's
  security middleware + chart silently filters extraEnvVars for reserved names).
- Use plain Kubernetes Deployment manifest at infra/manifests/mlflow/
  applied via Terraform null_resource.
- Use burakince/mlflow:2.1.1 image (bundles psycopg2 + boto3 — official
  ghcr.io/mlflow/mlflow images do NOT).
- If pinning a newer MLflow version: verify the image tag exists on Docker Hub
  BEFORE writing it into the manifest (docker pull <image>:<tag>).
- Schema migrations are forward-only: if database was migrated by MLflow X.Y,
  you cannot downgrade to MLflow X.Y-1 without DROPping + recreating the database.
